%BOM---------------------
Date:3/11/2010 1:27:38 AM
From:Paul Senior
CADC. To me, it's not their product that's innovative. It's that they have
mobile plants. I'm no expert here. I don't recall any USA ready-mix companies
that have these in use here though.

Gross margin for this quarter of course is $5.2M/$26M = 20%
Gross margin for the comparable quarter is $3.9/$10.8M = 36%
As reported: "Gross margin was 20.0% versus 36.5% in the same quarter last
year". So gross margin % fell.

Continuing to fog the mind, they felt they had to report another percentage:
That the gross profit did increase from $3.9M to $5.2 from the prior year
quarter, or "Gross profit increased 32.3% year-over-year to $5.2 million."

Okay, about "net earnings margin". Net profit margin this quarter was
$7.9M/$26M = 30% vs. $2.7M/$10.8M = 25%.

So we have this anomaly of net earnings margin this quarter of 30% exceeding
this year's gross margin of 20%. That's because apparently it's required that
$3.36M of "change in fair value of warrants" must be included now in moving
from gross to net. And this is also the place to include $1.3M of "other
subsidy income".

I'm one who tries to use net profit margins as a value criteria, and so I'm not
going to be liking non-recurring items (I hope they are non-recurring) such as
"change in fair value of warrants". They may invalidate conclusions I get when
I compare a company's profit margin performance year by year. As seen here,
these items can distort how how much <u>sales dollars</u> actually drop to the
bottom line.
%EOM----------------------

